The '''Sumatran ground cuckoo''' ('''''Carpococcyx viridis''''') is a large, [[Terrestrial animal|terrestrial]] species of [[cuckoo]] endemic to the forests of [[Sumatra]] in [[Indonesia]].{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|pp=1–2}} It was first described in 1879<ref name="Salvadori-1879">{{cite journal |last1=Salvadori |first1=Tommaso |author1-link=Tommaso Salvadori |date=1879 |title=Catalogo di una collezione di uccelli fatta nella parte occidentale di Sumatra dal Prof. Odoardo Beccari|trans-title=Catalogue of a collection of birds made in the western part of Sumatra by Prof. Odoardo Beccari |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/9186459 |journal=[[Museo_Civico_di_Storia_Naturale_Giacomo_Doria|Ann. Mus. Civ. Stor. Nat. Genova]] |volume=14 |publisher=Tip. del R. Istituto Sordo-Muti |page=187 |doi= |access-date=2025-05-07|language=Italian}}</ref> and, despite being identified as a separate species in the 1880s,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Finsch |first1=O. |author1-link=Otto Finsch |date= 1898 |title=On the specific distinction of the ground-cuckoos of Borneo and Sumatra |url=https://repository.naturalis.nl/pub/508723/ |journal=[[Notes from the Leyden Museum]] |volume=20 |issue=2/3 |publisher=[[Rijksmuseum van Natuurlijke Historie]] |pages=97–100 |access-date=2025-05-08}}</ref> was formerly considered [[conspecific]] with the [[Bornean ground cuckoo]] until recently being returned to the status of a unique species.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Long |first1=A. J. |last2=Collar |first2=N. J. |date=Feb 1995 |title=Taxonomy and names of ''Carpococcyx'' cuckoos from the Greater Sundas|url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/5c1a9e03f407b482a158da87/t/5c1fb71d0e2e7264c531ba82/1545582369032/Collar-Carpococcyx.pdf |journal=[[Forktail_(journal)|Forktail]] |volume=11 |publisher=Oriental Bird Club |pages=135–150 |access-date=2025-05-08}}</ref> Considered [[endangered]] species by the [[IUCN Red List]], it was initially known from just eight specimens and evaded notice from 1916 until 1997, when it was rediscovered and photographed.<ref name=":2" /> The Sumatran ground cuckoo's diet is thought to consist of invertebrates, small mammals, and reptiles.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.edgeofexistence.org/birds/species_info.php?id=2042|title=EDGE of Existence|website=EDGE of Existence|access-date=6 December 2017}}</ref>

== Description ==
The Sumatran ground cuckoo is a large bird of about {{Convert|55|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=1}} Its wings and long, full tail are glossy greenish-black, while its [[Mantle (bird anatomy)|mantle]], upper back, neck sides, lower throat, upper breast, [[Covert feather|covert feathers]], and [[secondary feathers]] are dull green.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=1}} Its crown is black, and the bare skin around its [[Bird vision|eyes]] are hues of green, lilac, and blue.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=1}} Its bill and legs are green, and its underparts below the upper breast are cinnamon buff.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=1}} [[BirdLife International]] describes its voice as follows: "Repeated low whistles (falling then rising in tone: WE-ow-WE), plus issued in a rising series (''we-ow-we'', ''we-ow-we'', ''we-ow-we'', ''we-ow-we''; each phrase slightly higher than last)."{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=1}}

== Distribution and habitat ==
The Sumatran ground cuckoo is [[Endemism|endemic]] to the [[Indonesia]]n island of [[Sumatra]].{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=2}} Notes on early specimen labels as well as recent sightings suggest its favoured habitat is foothills and primary [[Montane ecosystems|montane]] forest.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=4}}<ref name=":1" /> It has been found between elevations of {{convert|300 and 1400|m|ft|abbr=on|round=25}}, although recent sightings are exclusively from {{Convert|800–1000|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Payne |first1=Robert B. |url=https://www.hbw.com/species/sumatran-ground-cuckoo-carpococcyx-viridis |title=Handbook of the Birds of the World |last2=Sharpe |first2=Chris |year=2020 |editor-last1=Del Hoyo |editor-first1=Josep |language=en |chapter=Sumatran Ground-cuckoo (Carpococcyx viridis) |doi=10.2173/bow.sugcuc1.01 |access-date=6 December 2017 |editor-last2=Elliott |editor-first2=Andrew |editor-last3=Sargatal |editor-first3=Jordi |editor-last4=Christie |editor-first4=David |editor-last5=De Juana |editor-first5=Eduardo |url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=1}} Its small population makes it difficult to find, and like the [[Bornean ground cuckoo]], it may exhibit unobtrusive behavior – making sightings even more rare.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=2}}

Most modern-day sightings have taken place in the [[Barisan Mountains]] in [[South Sumatra]] and the [[Kerinci Seblat National Park]] of [[Jambi]] province, beginning with an individual photographed in [[Bukit Barisan Selatan National Park]] in 1997.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://datazone.birdlife.org/species/factsheet/sumatran-ground-cuckoo-carpococcyx-viridis/text|title=Sumatran Ground-cuckoo (Carpococcyx viridis) - BirdLife species factsheet|website=datazone.birdlife.org|access-date=6 December 2017}}</ref> An additional unconfirmed sighting took place in the [[Bukit Rimbang-Baling Wildlife Sanctuary]] in 2000.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=1}} In 2007, its call was recorded for the first time by [[Wildlife Conservation Society]] biologists after a trapper handed them a bird he had caught.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Lost Cuckoo Breaks Its Silence |date=9 March 2007 |publisher=[[Wildlife Conservation Society]] |url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2007/02/070227105511.htm |language=en |via=[[ScienceDaily]] |last1=Sautner |first1=Stephen |access-date=6 December 2017}}</ref> Up to five more sightings were reported nearby between 2007 and 2010.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=2}} In 2017, a camera trap in [[Batang Gadis National Park]] took a photo of a Sumatran ground cuckoo, indicating that a previously unknown population may exist in [[North Sumatra]].<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |last=Gokkon |first=Basten |date=27 September 2017 |title=Camera trap records nearly extinct cuckoo bird in Sumatra |url=https://news.mongabay.com/2017/09/camera-trap-records-nearly-extinct-cuckoo-bird-in-sumatra/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240522153402/https://news.mongabay.com/2017/09/camera-trap-records-nearly-extinct-cuckoo-bird-in-sumatra/ |archive-date=22 May 2024 |access-date=6 December 2017 |website=[[Mongabay]] |language=en-US}}</ref>

==Status and conservation==
{{See also|Palm oil production in Indonesia}}
Due to ongoing habitat loss and small population size, the [[IUCN Red List]] evaluates the Sumatran ground cuckoo as [[endangered]].{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=1}}<ref>{{Cite web |title=EDGE of Existence |url=http://www.edgeofexistence.org/birds/top_100.php |access-date=6 December 2017 |website=EDGE of Existence}}</ref> The Red List estimates that the total population of Sumatran ground cuckoos ranges from 50 to 249 mature individuals, and its population is thought to be decreasing.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=4}} The bird's known range overlaps with some of the [[Barisan Mountains]]' 20 protected areas,<ref name=":2" />{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=4}} but rapid [[deforestation]] – its main threat – is prevalent even in these areas.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=4}}{{sfn|Kinnaird|Sanderson|O'Brien|Wibisono|2003|pp=245–246}} A 2003 study showed an average 2% loss of forest within Bukit Barisan Selatan National Park, part of its known range,{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=2}} between 1985 and 1999.{{sfn|Kinnaird|Sanderson|O'Brien|Wibisono|2003|p=245}} This deforestation is caused predominantly by logging, [[Palm oil production in Indonesia|palm oil plantations]], [[pulpwood]] plantations, establishment of farms, and [[wildfire]]s.{{sfn|Kinnaird|Sanderson|O'Brien|Wibisono|2003|p=246}} The species likely benefits from protected areas, but its conservation needs are not fully understood due to a lack of study.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2017|p=4–5}}

